    "input": "A 72-year-old Caucasian female from an urban area with over 200,000 residents and an average annual sunshine of 2299 hours (latitude 44°10′50.63′′ N and longitude 28°38′3.55′′ E) visited the Dermatology Clinic of an academic hospital in August 2022. She reported recent changes in multiple melanocytic lesions on various skin areas. Her family history included essential arterial hypertension and diabetes mellitus in her mother and prostate cancer in her father, with no significant skin conditions in close relatives. The patient had personal medical conditions such as arterial hypertension and dyslipidemia. She was retired, having previously worked as a call center representative with no professional ultraviolet radiation exposure. Her sun-damage risk factors included Fitzpatrick phototype II and a history of childhood sunburns. There were no issues related to healthcare access, cultural, or financial matters. Clinical and dermoscopic assessments revealed Fitzpatrick phototype II and approximately 30 pigmented nevi with irregular shapes, varying colors (light to dark brown), and different sizes. Total body mapping (TBM) was used for photographic documentation of the entire body surface, followed by sequential digital dermoscopy (FotoFinder bodystudio ATBM master system, 4th Generation, FotoFinder Systems GmbH, Bad Birnbach, Germany) of specific melanocytic lesions to monitor their changes over time and identify any new lesions. Four melanocytic lesions showed features such as irregular borders, shiny white streaks, and an irregular pigmented network, leading to the decision for surgical excision.",
